t_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=From+Marx+to+Mises%3A+Post-Capitalist+Society+and+the+Challenge+of+Economic+Calculation&amp;rft.pages=43&amp;rft.pub=Open+Court+Publishing+Company&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-87548-449-5&amp;rft.aulast=Steele&amp;rft.aufirst=David&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt108" id="mwB3Q"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt108" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwB3U"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-Steele_1992_44-45-49" id="cite_note-Steele_1992_44-45-49"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-Steele_1992_44-45_49-0" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-Steele_1992_44-45-49" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt109" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Steele"},"first":{"wt":"David"},"title":{"wt":"From Marx to Mises: Post-Capitalist Society and the Challenge of Economic Calculation"},"publisher":{"wt":"Open Court Publishing Company"},"year":{"wt":"1992"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-87548-449-5"},"pages":{"wt":"44–45"},"quote":{"wt":"By 1888, the term &apos;socialism&apos; was in general use among Marxists, who had dropped &apos;communism&apos;, now considered an old fashioned term meaning the same as &apos;socialism&apos; ... At the turn of the century, Marxists called themselves socialists ... The definition of socialism and communism as successive stages was introduced into Marxist theory by Lenin in 1917 ... the new distinction was helpful to Lenin in defending his party against the traditional Marxist criticism that Russia was too backward for a socialist revolution."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwB3Y">Steele, David (1992). <i id="mwB3c">From Marx to Mises: Post-Capitalist Society and the Challenge of Economic Calculation</i>. Open Court Publishing Company. pp.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwB3g"> </span>44–45. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwB3k">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwB3o"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-87548-449-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-87548-449-5" id="mwB3s">978-0-87548-449-5</a>. <q id="mwB3w">By 1888, the term 'socialism' was in general use among Marxists, who had dropped 'communism', now considered an old fashioned term meaning the same as 'socialism' ... At the turn of the century, Marxists called themselves socialists ... The definition of socialism and communism as successive stages was introduced into Marxist theory by Lenin in 1917 ... the new distinction was helpful to Lenin in defending his party against the traditional Marxist criticism that Russia was too backward for a socialist revolution.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=From+Marx+to+Mises%3A+Post-Capitalist+Society+and+the+Challenge+of+Economic+Calculation&amp;rft.pages=44-45&amp;rft.pub=Open+Court+Publishing+Company&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-87548-449-5&amp;rft.aulast=Steele&amp;rft.aufirst=David&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt109" id="mwB30"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt109" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwB34"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-50" id="cite_note-50"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-50" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-50" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt120" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Busky"},"first":{"wt":"Donald F."},"title":{"wt":"Democratic Socialism: A Global Survey"},"publisher":{"wt":"Praeger"},"date":{"wt":"2000"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-275-96886-1"},"page":{"wt":"9"},"quote":{"wt":"In a modern sense of the word, communism refers to the ideology of Marxism-Leninism."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwB38">Busky, Donald F. (2000). <i id="mwB4A">Democratic Socialism: A Global Survey</i>. Praeger. p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwB4E"> </span>9. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwB4I">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwB4M"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-275-96886-1" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-275-96886-1" id="mwB4Q">978-0-275-96886-1</a>. <q id="mwB4U">In a modern sense of the word, communism refers to the ideology of Marxism-Leninism.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Democratic+Socialism%3A+A+Global+Survey&amp;rft.pages=9&amp;rft.pub=Praeger&amp;rft.date=2000&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-275-96886-1&amp;rft.aulast=Busky&amp;rft.aufirst=Donald+F.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt120" id="mwB4Y"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt120" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwB4c"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-51" id="cite_note-51"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-51" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-51" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt121" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Williams"},"first":{"wt":"Raymond"},"title":{"wt":"Keywords: A vocabulary of culture and society, revised edition"},"publisher":{"wt":"Oxford University Press"},"year":{"wt":"1983"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-19-520469-8"},"page":{"wt":"289"},"chapter":{"wt":"Socialism"},"quote":{"wt":"The decisive distinction between socialist and communist, as in one sense these terms are now ordinarily used, came with the renaming, in 1918, of the Russian Social-Democratic Labour Party (Bolsheviks) as the All-Russian Communist Party (Bolsheviks). From that time on, a distinction of socialist from communist, often with supporting definitions such as social democrat or democratic socialist, became widely current, although it is significant that all communist parties, in line with earlier usage, continued to describe themselves as socialist and dedicated to socialism."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwB4g">Williams, Raymond (1983). "Socialism". <i id="mwB4k">Keywords: A vocabulary of culture and society, revised edition</i>. Oxford University Press. p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwB4o"> </span>289. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwB4s">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwB4w"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-19-520469-8" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-19-520469-8" id="mwB40">978-0-19-520469-8</a>. <q id="mwB44">The decisive distinction between socialist and communist, as in one sense these terms are now ordinarily used, came with the renaming, in 1918, of the Russian Social-Democratic Labour Party (Bolsheviks) as the All-Russian Communist Party (Bolsheviks). From that time on, a distinction of socialist from communist, often with supporting definitions such as social democrat or democratic socialist, became widely current, although it is significant that all communist parties, in line with earlier usage, continued to describe themselves as socialist and dedicated to socialism.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Socialism&amp;rft.btitle=Keywords%3A+A+vocabulary+of+culture+and+society%2C+revised+edition&amp;rft.pages=289&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=1983&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-19-520469-8&amp;rft.aulast=Williams&amp;rft.aufirst=Raymond&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt121" id="mwB48"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt121" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwB5A"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-52" id="cite_note-52"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-52" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-52" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt128" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Williams"},"first":{"wt":"Raymond"},"authorlink":{"wt":"Raymond Williams"},"title":{"wt":"Keywords: a vocabulary of culture and society"},"publisher":{"wt":"Fontana"},"year":{"wt":"1976"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-00-633479-8"},"title-link":{"wt":"Keywords: A Vocabulary of Culture and Society"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwB5E"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Raymond_Williams" title="Raymond Williams" id="mwB5I">Williams, Raymond</a> (1976). <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Keywords:_A_Vocabulary_of_Culture_and_Society" title="Keywords: A Vocabulary of Culture and Society" id="mwB5M"><i id="mwB5Q">Keywords: a vocabulary of culture and society</i></a>. Fontana. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="Int