}]}'>Hirsch, Donald; Kett, Joseph F.; Trefil, James S. (2002), <i id="mwCQ4">The New Dictionary of Cultural Literacy</i>, Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCQ8"> </span>316, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwCRA">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCRE"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-618-22647-4" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-618-22647-4" id="mwCRI">978-0-618-22647-4</a>, <q id="mwCRM">Eastern Bloc. The name applied to the former communist states of eastern Europe, including Yugoslavia and Albania, as well as the countries of the Warsaw Pact</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+New+Dictionary+of+Cultural+Literacy&amp;rft.pages=316&amp;rft.pub=Houghton+Mifflin+Harcourt&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-618-22647-4&amp;rft.aulast=Hirsch&amp;rft.aufirst=Donald&amp;rft.au=Kett%2C+Joseph+F.&amp;rft.au=Trefil%2C+James+S.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt728" id="mwCRQ"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt728" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwCRU"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-154" id="cite_note-154"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-154" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-154" class="mw-reference-text"><cite id="CITEREFSatyendra2003" class="citation" about="#mwt729" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"citation ","href":"./Template:Citation"},"params":{"last1":{"wt":"Satyendra"},"first1":{"wt":"Kush"},"title":{"wt":"Encyclopaedic dictionary of political science"},"publisher":{"wt":"Sarup &amp; Sons"},"year":{"wt":"2003"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-81-7890-071-1"},"page":{"wt":"65"},"quote":{"wt":"\"the countries of Eastern Europe under communism\""}},"i":0}}]}'>Satyendra, Kush (2003), <i id="mwCRY">Encyclopaedic dictionary of political science</i>, Sarup &amp; Sons, p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCRc"> </span>65, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwCRg">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCRk"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-81-7890-071-1" title="Special:BookSources/978-81-7890-071-1" id="mwCRo">978-81-7890-071-1</a>, <q id="mwCRs">the countries of Eastern Europe under communism</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Encyclopaedic+dictionary+of+political+science&amp;rft.pages=65&amp;rft.pub=Sarup+%26+Sons&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.isbn=978-81-7890-071-1&amp;rft.aulast=Satyendra&amp;rft.aufirst=Kush&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt729" id="mwCRw"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt729" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwCR0"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-155" id="cite_note-155"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-155" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-155" class="mw-reference-text">Compare: <cite class="citation book" about="#mwt730" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Janzen"},"first":{"wt":"Jörg"},"last2":{"wt":"Taraschewski"},"first2":{"wt":"Thomas"},"editor-last":{"wt":"Shahshahānī"},"editor-first":{"wt":"Suhaylā"},"title":{"wt":"Cities of Pilgrimage"},"url":{"wt":"https://books.google.com/books?id=0T7DAJqAN7wC"},"accessdate":{"wt":"21 December 2012"},"series":{"wt":"Iuaes-series"},"volume":{"wt":"4"},"year":{"wt":"2009"},"publisher":{"wt":"LIT Verlag"},"location":{"wt":"Münster"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-3-8258-1618-6"},"page":{"wt":"190"},"quote":{"wt":"Until 1990, despite being a formally independent state, Mongolia had de facto been an integral part of the Soviet dominated Eastern Bloc."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwCR4">Janzen, Jörg; Taraschewski, Thomas (2009).  Shahshahānī, Suhaylā, ed. <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=0T7DAJqAN7wC" id="mwCR8"><i id="mwCSA">Cities of Pilgrimage</i></a>. Iuaes-series. <b id="mwCSE">4</b>. Münster: LIT Verlag. p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCSI"> </span>190. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwCSM">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCSQ"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-3-8258-1618-6" title="Special:BookSources/978-3-8258-1618-6" id="mwCSU">978-3-8258-1618-6</a><span class="reference-accessdate" id="mwCSY">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap" id="mwCSc">21 December</span> 2012</span>. <q id="mwCSg">Until 1990, despite being a formally independent state, Mongolia had de facto been an integral part of the Soviet dominated Eastern Bloc.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Cities+of+Pilgrimage&amp;rft.place=M%C3%BCnster&amp;rft.series=Iuaes-series&amp;rft.pages=190&amp;rft.pub=LIT+Verlag&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.isbn=978-3-8258-1618-6&amp;rft.aulast=Janzen&amp;rft.aufirst=J%C3%B6rg&amp;rft.au=Taraschewski%2C+Thomas&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D0T7DAJqAN7wC&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt730" id="mwCSk"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt730" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwCSo"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-156" id="cite_note-156"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-156" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-156" class="mw-reference-text">John Rettie, <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/4723942.stm" id="mwCSs">"The day Khrushchev denounced Stalin"</a>, BBC, 18 February 2006.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-157" id="cite_note-157"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-157" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-157" class="mw-reference-text">Within the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Italian_Communist_Party" title="Italian Communist Party" id="mwCSw">Italian Communist Party</a> (PCI) a split ensued: most ordinary members and the Party leadership, including <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Palmiro_Togliatti" title="Palmiro Togliatti" id="mwCS0">Palmiro Togliatti</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Giorgio_Napolitano" title="Giorgio Napolitano" id="mwCS4">Giorgio Napolitano</a>, regarded the Hungarian insurgents as counter-revolutionaries, as reported in <i id="mwCS8"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./L'Unità" title="L'Unità" id="mwCTA">l'Unità</a></i>, the official PCI newspaper. The following are references in English on the conflicting positions of <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,808752,00.html" id="mwCTE"><i id="mwCTI">l'Unità</i></a>, <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,808824,00.html" id="mwCTM">Antonio Giolitti and party boss Palmiro Togliatti</a>, <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,868066,00.html" id="mwCTQ">Giuseppe Di Vittorio</a> and <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Pietro-Nenni" id="mwCTU">Pietro Nenni</a>.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-158" id="cite_note-158"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-158" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-158" class="mw-reference-text">However, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Giuseppe_Di_Vittorio" title="Giuseppe Di Vittorio" id="mwCTY">Giuseppe Di Vittorio</a> (chief of the Communist trade union <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./CGIL" title="CGIL" id="mwCTc" class="mw-redirect">CGIL</a>) repudiated the leadership position as did the prominent party members <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Antonio_Giolitti" title="Antonio Giolitti" id="mwCTg">Antonio Giolitti</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Loris_Fortuna" title="Loris Fortuna" id="mwCTk">Loris Fortuna</a> and many other influential communist intellectuals, who later were expelled or left the party. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Pietro_Nenni" title="Pietro Nenni" id="mwCTo">Pietro Nenni</a>, the national secretary of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Italian_Socialist_Party" title="Italian Socialist Party" id="mwCTs">Italian Socialist Party</a>, a close ally of the PCI, opposed the Soviet intervention as well. Napolitano, elected in 2006 as <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./President_of_the_Italian_Republic" title="President of the Italian Republic" id="mwCTw" class="mw-redirect">President of the Italian Republic</a>, wrote in his 2005 political autobiography that he regretted his justification of Soviet action in Hungary and that at the time he believed in party unity and the international leadership of Soviet communism.<cite class="citation book" about="#mwt731" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Napolitano"},"first":{"wt":"Giorgio"},"year":{"wt":"2005"},"title":{"wt":"Dal Pci al socialismo europeo. Un&apos;autobiografia politica (From the Communist Party to European Socialism. A political autobiography)"},"publisher":{"wt":"Laterza"},"language":{"wt":"Italian"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-88-420-7715-2"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwCT0">Napolitano, Giorgio (2005). <i id="mwCT4">Dal Pci al socialismo europeo. Un'autobiografia politica (From the Communist Party to European Socialism. A political autobiography)</i> (in Italian). Laterza. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwCT8">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCUA"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-88-420-7715-2" title="Special:BookSources/978-88-420-7715-2" id="mwCUE">978-88-420-7715-2</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Dal+Pci+al+socialismo+europeo.+Un%27autobiografia+politica+%28From+the+Communist+Party+to+European+Socialism.+A+political+autobiography%29&amp;rft.pub=Laterza&amp;rft.date=2005&amp;rft.isbn=978-88-420-7715-2&amp;rft.aulast=Napolitano&amp;rft.aufirst=Giorgio&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt731" id="mwCUI"></span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:CS1_Italian-language_sources_(it)" about="#mwt731" id="mwCUM"/><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt731" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwCUQ"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-159" id="cite_note-159"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-159" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-159" class="mw-reference-text">

Within the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Communist_Party_of_Great_Britain" title="Communist Party of Great Britain" id="mwCUU">Communist Party of Great Britain</a> (CPGB), dissent that began with the repudiation of Stalin by <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./John_Saville" title="John Saville" id="mwCUY">John Saville</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./E.P._Thompson" title="E.P. Thompson" id="mwCUc" class="mw-redirect">E.P. Thompson</a>, influential historians and members of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Communist_Party_Historians_Group" title="Communist Party Historians Group" id="mwCUg">Communist Party Historians Group</a>, culminated in a loss of thousands of party members as events unfolded in Hungary. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Peter_Fryer" title="Peter Fryer" id="mwCUk">Peter Fryer</a>, correspondent for the CPGB newspaper <i id="mwCUo"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Morning_Star_(UK_newspaper)" title="Morning Star (UK newspaper)" id="mwCUs" class="mw-redirect">The Daily Worker</a></i>, reported accurately on the violent suppression of the uprising, but his dispatches were heavily censored; Fryer resigned from the paper upon his return, and was later expelled from the Communist Party. Fryer, Peter (1957). Hungarian Tragedy. London: D. Dobson. Chapter 9 (The Second Soviet Intervention). <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Amazon_Standard_Identification_Number" title="Amazon Standard Identification Number" about="#mwt732" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"ASIN","href":"./Template:ASIN"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"B0007J7674"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwCUw">ASIN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt732" id="mwCU0"> </span><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0007J7674" about="#mwt732" id="mwCU4">B0007J7674</a>.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-160" id="cite_note-160"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-160" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-160" class="mw-reference-text">

In France, moderate Communists, such as historian <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Emmanuel_Le_Roy_Ladurie" title="Emmanuel Le Roy Ladurie" id="mwCU8">Emmanuel Le Roy Ladurie</a>, resigned, questioning the policy of supporting Soviet actions by the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./French_Communist_Party" title="French Communist Party" id="mwCVA">French Communist Party</a>. The French anarchist philosopher and writer <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Albert_Camus" title="Albert Camus" id="mwCVE">Albert Camus</a> wrote an <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Open_letter" title="Open letter" id="mwCVI">open letter</a>, <i id="mwCVM"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./The_Blood_of_the_Hungarians" title="The Blood of the Hungarians" id="mwCVQ" class="mw-redirect">The Blood of the Hungarians</a></i>, criticising the West's lack of action. Even <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Jean-Paul_Sartre" title="Jean-Paul Sartre" id="mwCVU">Jean-Paul Sartre</a>, still a determined Communist Party member, criticised the Soviets in his article <i id="mwCVY">Le Fantôme de Staline</i>, in <i id="mwCVc">Situations VII</i>. Sartre, Jean-Paul (1956), <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.humanite.presse.fr/journal/2005-06-21/2005-06-21-809020" id="mwCVg">L’intellectuel et les communistes français <span class="languageicon" about="#mwt733" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"fr icon","href":"./Template:Fr_icon"},"params":{},"i":0}}]}' id="mwCVk">(in French)</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_with_French-language_external_links" about="#mwt733" id="mwCVo"/></a><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:All_articles_with_dead_external_links" about="#mwt734" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"dead link","href":"./Template:Dead_link"},"params":{"date":{"wt":"June 2017"},"bot":{"wt":"InternetArchiveBot"},"fix-attempted":{"wt":"yes"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwCVs"/><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_with_dead_external_links_from_June_2017" about="#mwt734" id="mwCVw"/><sup class="noprint Inline-Template" about="#mwt734" id="mwCV0"><span style="white-space: nowrap;" id="mwCV4"><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCV8">[</span><i id="mwCWA"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Wikipedia:Link_rot" title="Wikipedia:Link rot" id="mwCWE"><span title=" Dead link since June 2017" id="mwCWI">permanent dead link</span></a></i><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCWM">]</span></span></sup><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_with_permanently_dead_external_links" about="#mwt734" id="mwCWQ"/> Le Web de l'Humanite, 21 June 2005. Retrieved 24 October 2006.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-161" id="cite_note-161"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-161" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-161" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt742" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Dirlik"},"first":{"wt":"Arif"},"url":{"wt":"https://books.google.com/books?id=S-aGLEtx7AYC&amp;pg=PA20"},"title":{"wt":"The Marxism in the Chinese revolution"},"year":{"wt":"2005"},"publisher":{"wt":"Rowman &amp; Littlefield"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-7425-3069-0"},"page":{"wt":"20"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwCWU">Dirlik, Arif (2005). <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=S-aGLEtx7AYC&amp;pg=PA20" id="mwCWY"><i id="mwCWc">The Marxism in the Chinese revolution</i></a>. Rowman &amp; Littlefield. p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCWg"> </span>20. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwCWk">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCWo"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-7425-3069-0" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-7425-3069-0" id="mwCWs">978-0-7425-3069-0</a>.</cite><span ti