Rosberg+Jr.&amp;rft.aufirst=William+and+Carl&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt746" id="mwCYA"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt746" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwCYE"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-165" id="cite_note-165"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-165" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-165" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=98937598" id="mwCYI">"Cuba Marks 50 Years Since 'Triumphant Revolution'"</a>. Jason Beaubien. NPR. 1 January 2009. Retrieved 9 July 2013.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-166" id="cite_note-166"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-166" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-166" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt754" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Robinson"},"first":{"wt":"Geoffrey B."},"date":{"wt":"2018"},"title":{"wt":"The Killing Season: A History of the Indonesian Massacres, 1965–66"},"url":{"wt":"https://press.princeton.edu/titles/11135.html"},"location":{"wt":""},"publisher":{"wt":"[[Princeton University Press]]"},"page":{"wt":"203"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-1-4008-8886-3"},"quote":{"wt":"a US Embassy official in Jakarta, Robert Martens, had supplied the Indonesian Army with lists containing the names of thousands of PKI officials in the months after the alleged coup attempt. According to the journalist Kathy Kadane, \"As many as 5,000 names were furnished over a period of months to the Army there, and the Americans later checked off the names of those who had been killed or captured.\" Despite Martens later denials of any such intent, these actions almost certainly aided in the death or detention of many innocent people. They also sent a powerful message that the US government agreed with and supported the army&apos;s campaign against the PKI, even as that campaign took its terrible toll in human lives."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwCYM">Robinson, Geoffrey B. (2018). <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://press.princeton.edu/titles/11135.html" id="mwCYQ"><i id="mwCYU">The Killing Season: A History of the Indonesian Massacres, 1965–66</i></a>. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Princeton_University_Press" title="Princeton University Press" id="mwCYY">Princeton University Press</a>. p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCYc"> </span>203. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwCYg">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCYk"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-1-4008-8886-3" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-4008-8886-3" id="mwCYo">978-1-4008-8886-3</a>. <q id="mwCYs">a US Embassy official in Jakarta, Robert Martens, had supplied the Indonesian Army with lists containing the names of thousands of PKI officials in the months after the alleged coup attempt. According to the journalist Kathy Kadane, "As many as 5,000 names were furnished over a period of months to the Army there, and the Americans later checked off the names of those who had been killed or captured." Despite Martens later denials of any such intent, these actions almost certainly aided in the death or detention of many innocent people. They also sent a powerful message that the US government agreed with and supported the army's campaign against the PKI, even as that campaign took its terrible toll in human lives.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Killing+Season%