art of the rich and (relatively) stable capitalist world. Many of the other countries are falling behind, and some are so far behind that they cannot aspire to go back to the point where they were when the Wall fell for several decades.\""}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwCr4"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Branko_Milanović" title="Branko Milanović" id="mwCr8">Milanović, Branko</a> (2015). "After the Wall Fell: The Poor Balance Sheet of the Transition to Capitalism". <i id="mwCsA"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Challenge_(economics_magazine)" title="Challenge (economics magazine)" id="mwCsE">Challenge</a></i>. <b id="mwCsI">58</b> (2): 135–138. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier" id="mwCsM">doi</a>:<a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1080%2F05775132.2015.1012402" id="mwCsQ">10.1080/05775132.2015.1012402</a>. <q id="mwCsU">So, what is the balance sheet of transition? Only three or at most five or six countries could be said to be on the road to becoming a part of the rich and (relatively) stable capitalist world. Many of the other countries are falling behind, and some are so far behind that they cannot aspire to go back to the point where they were when the Wall fell for several decades.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Challenge&amp;rft.atitle=After+the+Wall+Fell%3A+The+Poor+Balance+Sheet+of+the+Transition+to+Capitalism&amp;rft.volume=58&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.pages=135-138&amp;rft.date=2015&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1080%2F05775132.2015.1012402&amp;rft.aulast=Milanovi%C4%87&amp;rft.aufirst=Branko&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt969" id="mwCsY"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt969" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwCsc"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-219" id="cite_note-219"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-219" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-219" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt970" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Ghodsee"},"first":{"wt":"Kristen"},"date":{"wt":"2017"},"title":{"wt":"Red Hangover: Legacies of Twentieth-Century Communism"},"url":{"wt":"https://www.dukeupress.edu/red-hangover"},"location":{"wt":""},"publisher":{"wt":"[[Duke University Press]]"},"pages":{"wt":"xix–xx, 134, 197–200"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-8223-6949-3"},"author-link":{"wt":"Kristen Ghodsee"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwCsg"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kristen_Ghodsee" title="Kristen Ghodsee" id="mwCsk">Ghodsee, Kristen</a> (2017). <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://www.dukeupress.edu/red-hangover" id="mwCso"><i id="mwCss">Red Hangover: Legacies of Twentieth-Century Communism</i></a>. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Duke_University_Press" title="Duke University Press" id="mwCsw">Duke University Press</a>. pp.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCs0"> </span>xix–xx, 134, 197–200. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwCs4">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwCs8"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-8223-6949-3" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-8223-6949-3" id="mwCtA">978-0-8223-6949-3</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Red+Hangover%3A+Legacies+of+Twentieth-Century+Communism&amp;rft.pages=xix-xx%2C+134%2C+197-200&amp;rft.pub=Duke+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2017&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8223-6949-3&amp;rft.aulast=Ghodsee&amp;rft.aufirst=Kristen&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukeupress.edu%2Fred-hangover&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt970" id="mwCtE"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt970" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwCtI"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-220" id="cite_note-220"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-220" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-220" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation web" about="#mwt971" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite web ","href":"./Template:Cite_web"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"https://aeon.co/essays/the-merits-of-taking-an-anti-anti-communism-stance"},"title":{"wt":"Anti-anti-communism"},"last1":{"wt":"Ghodsee"},"first1":{"wt":"Kristen R."},"last2":{"wt":"Sehon"},"first2":{"wt":"Scott"},"date":{"wt":"March 22, 2018"},"website":{"wt":"[[Aeon (digital magazine)|Aeon]]"},"publisher":{"wt":""},"access-date":{"wt":"September 26, 2018"},"authorlink":{"wt":"Kristen Ghodsee"},"authorlink2":{"wt":"Scott Sehon"},"quote":{"wt":"\"A 2009 poll in eight east European countries asked if the economic situation for ordinary people was ‘better, worse or about the same as it was under communism’. The results stunned observers: 72 per cent of Hungarians, and 62 per cent of both Ukrainians and Bulgarians believed that most people were worse off after 1989. In no country did more than 47 per cent of those surveyed agree that their lives improved after the advent of free markets. Subsequent polls and qualitative research across Russia and eastern Europe confirm the persistence of these sentiments as popular discontent with the failed promises of free-market prosperity has grown, especially among older people.\""}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwCtM"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kristen_Ghodsee" title="Kristen Ghodsee" id="mwCtQ">Ghodsee, Kristen R.</a>; <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Scott_Sehon" title="Scott Sehon" id="mwCtU">Sehon, Scott</a> (March 22, 2018). <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://aeon.co/essays/the-merits-of-taking-an-anti-anti-communism-stance" id="mwCtY">"Anti-anti-communism"</a>. <i id="mwCtc"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Aeon_(digital_magazine)" title="Aeon (digital magazine)" id="mwCtg">Aeon</a></i><span class="reference-accessdate" id="mwCtk">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap" id="mwCto">September 26,</span> 2018</span>. <q id="mwCts">A 2009 poll in eight east European countries asked if the economic situation for ordinary people was ‘better, worse or about the same as it was under communism’. The results stunned observers: 72 per cent of Hungarians, and 62 per cent of both Ukrainians and Bulgarians believed that most people were worse off after 1989. In no country did more than 47 per cent of those surveyed agree that their lives improved after the advent of free markets. Subsequent polls and qualitative research across Russia and eastern Europe confirm the persistence of these sentiments as popular discontent with the failed promises of free-market prosperity has grown, especially among older people.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=Aeon&amp;rft.atitle=Anti-anti-communism&amp;rft.date=2018-03-22&amp;rft.aulast=Ghodsee&amp;rft.aufirst=Kristen+R.&amp;rft.au=Sehon%2C+Scott&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Faeon.co%2Fessays%2Fthe-merits-of-taking-an-anti-anti-communism-stance&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt971" id="mwCtw"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt971" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id