note-Market_Socialism:_The_Debate_Among_Socialists,_1998._pp._60–61-301"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-Market_Socialism:_The_Debate_Among_Socialists,_1998._pp._60–61_301-0" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-Market_Socialism:_The_Debate_Among_Socialists,_1998._pp._60–61-301" class="mw-reference-text"><i id="mwDJI">Market Socialism: The Debate Among Socialists</i>, 1998. pp. 60–61"</span></li><li about="#cite_note-302" id="cite_note-302"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-302" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-302" class="mw-reference-text">in Encyclopædia Britannica (2009). Retrieved 14 October 2009, from Encyclopædia Britannica Online: <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external free" href="http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/551569/socialism" id="mwDJM">http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/551569/socialism</a>, "Main" summary: "Socialists complain that capitalism necessarily leads to unfair and exploitative concentrations of wealth and power in the hands of the relative few who emerge victorious from free-market competition—people who then use their wealth and power to reinforce their dominance in society."</span></li><li about="#cite_note-ReferenceA-303" id="cite_note-ReferenceA-303"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-ReferenceA_303-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-ReferenceA_303-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-ReferenceA-303" class="mw-reference-text">Karl Marx, Preface to A Contribution to the Critique of Political Economy, 1859</span></li><li about="#cite_note-ComparingEconomic-304" id="cite_note-ComparingEconomic-304"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-ComparingEconomic_304-0" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-ComparingEconomic-304"