t="#mwt1361" id="mwDM0"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt1361" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwDM4"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-314" id="cite_note-314"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-314" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-314" class="mw-reference-text">Schaff, Adam, 'Marxist Theory on Revolution and Violence', p. 263. in Journal of the history of ideas, Vol 34, no. 2 (April–June 1973)</span></li><li about="#cite_note-315" id="cite_note-315"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-315" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-315" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt1371" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Bockman"},"first":{"wt":"Johanna"},"title":{"wt":"Markets in the name of Socialism: The Left-Wing origins of Neoliberalism"},"publisher":{"wt":"Stanford University Press"},"year":{"wt":"2011"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-8047-7566-3"},"page":{"wt":"20"},"quote":{"wt":"According to nineteenth-century socialist views, socialism would function without capitalist economic categories—such as money, prices, interest, profits and rent—and thus would function according to laws other than those described by current economic science. While some socialists recognised the need for money and prices at least during the transition from capitalism to socialism, socialists more commonly believed that the socialist economy would soon administratively mobilise the economy in physical units without the use of prices or money."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwDM8">Bockman, Johanna (2011). <i id="mwDNA">Markets in the name of Socialism: The Left-Wing origins of Neoliberalism</i>. Stanford University Press. p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwDNE"> </span>20. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwDNI">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwDNM"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-8047-7566-3" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-8047-7566-3" id="mwDNQ">978-0-8047-7566-3</a>. <q id="mwDNU">According to nineteenth-century socialist views, socialism would function without capitalist economic categories—such as money, prices, interest, profits and rent—and thus would function according to laws other than those described by current economic science. While some socialists recognised the need for money and prices at least during the transition from capitalism to socialism, socialists more commonly believed that the socialist economy would soon administratively mobilise the economy in physical units without the use of prices or money.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Markets+in+the+name+of+Socialism%3A+The+Left-Wing+origins+of+Neoliberalism&amp;rft.pages=20&amp;rft.pub=Stanford+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2011&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8047-7566-3&amp;rft.aulast=Bockman&amp;rft.aufirst=Johanna&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt1371" id="mwDNY"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt1371" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwDNc"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-316" id="cite_note-316"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-316" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-316" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt1372" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Gregory and Stuart"},"first":{"wt":"Paul and Robert"},"title":{"wt":"Comparing Economic Systems in the Twenty-First Century, Seventh Edition: \"Socialist Economy\""},"publisher":{"wt":"George Hoffman"},"year":{"wt":"2004"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-618-26181-9"},"page":{"wt":"117"},"quote":{"wt":"In such a setting, information problems are not serious, and engineers rather than economists can resolve the issue of factor proportions."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwDNg">Gregory and Stuart, Paul and Robert (2004). <i id="mwDNk">Comparing Economic Systems in the Twenty-First Century, Seventh Edition: "Socialist Economy"</i>. George Hoffman. p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwDNo"> </span>117. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwDNs">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwDNw"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-618-26181-9" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-618-26181-9" id="mwDN0">978-0-618-26181-9</a>. <q id="mwDN4">In such a setting, information problems are not serious, and engineers rather than economists can resolve the issue of factor proportions.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Comparing+Economic+Systems+in+the+Twenty-First+Century%2C+Seventh+Edition%3A+%22Socialist+Economy%22&amp;rft.pages=117&amp;rft.pub=George+Hoffman&amp;rft.date=2004&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-618-26181-9&amp;rft.aulast=Gregory+and+Stuart&amp;rft.aufirst=Paul+and+Robert&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt1372" id="mwDN8"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt1372" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwDOA"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-317" id="cite_note-317"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-317" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-317" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt1376" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"O&apos;Hara"},"first":{"wt":"Phillip"},"title":{"wt":"Encyclopedia of Political Economy, Volume 2"},"publisher":{"wt":"[[Routledge]]"},"date":{"wt":"2003"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-415-24187-8"},"page":{"wt":"70"},"quote":{"wt":"Market socialism is a general designation for a number of models of economic systems. On the one hand, the market mechanism is utilised to distribute economic output, to organise production and to allocate factor inputs. On the other hand, the economic surplus accrues to society at large rather than to a class of private (capitalist) owners, through some form of collective, public or social ownership of capital."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwDOE">O'Hara, Phillip (2003). <i id="mwDOI">Encyclopedia of Political Economy, Volume 2</i>. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Routledge" title="Routledge" id="mwDOM">Routledge</a>. p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwDOQ"> </span>70. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwDOU">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwDOY"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-415-24187-8" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-415-24187-8" id="mwDOc">978-0-415-24187-8</a>. <q id="mwDOg">Market socialism is a general designation for a number of models of economic systems. On the one hand, the market mechanism is utilised to distribute economic output, to organise production and to allocate factor inputs. On the other hand, the economic surplus accrues to society at large rather than to a class of private (capitalist) owners, through some form of collective, public or social ownership of capital.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Encyclopedia+of+Political+Economy%2C+Volume+2&amp;rft.pages=70&amp;rft.pub=Routledge&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-415-24187-8&amp;rft.aulast=O%27Hara&amp;rft.aufirst=Phillip&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt1376" id="mwDOk"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt1376" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwDOo"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-318" id="cite_note-318"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-318" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-318" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt1377" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Stiglitz"},"first":{"wt":"Joseph"},"title":{"wt":"Whither Socialism?"},"publisher":{"wt":"The MIT Press"},"date":{"wt":"1996"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-262-69182-6"},"quote":{"wt":"."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwDOs">Stiglitz, Joseph (1996). <i id="mwDOw">Whither Socialism?</i>. The MIT Press. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwDO0">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwDO4"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-262-69182-6" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-262-69182-6" id="mwDO8">978-0-262-69182-6</a>. <q id="mwDPA">.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Whither+Socialism%3F&amp;rft.pub=The+MIT+Press&amp;rft.date=1996&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-262-69182-6&amp;rft.aulast=Stiglitz&amp;rft