48"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-348" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-348" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation journal" about="#mwt1733" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite journal ","href":"./Template:Cite_journal"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Hardcastle"},"first":{"wt":"Edgar"},"authorlink":{"wt":"Edgar Hardcastle"},"title":{"wt":"The Nationalisation of the Railways"},"journal":{"wt":"[[Socialist Standard]]"},"volume":{"wt":"43"},"issue":{"wt":"1"},"year":{"wt":"1947"},"url":{"wt":"http://www.marxists.org/archive/hardcastle/1947/02/railways.htm"},"accessdate":{"wt":"28 April 2007"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwDY0"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Edgar_Hardcastle" title="Edgar Hardcastle" id="mwDY4">Hardcastle, Edgar</a> (1947). <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.marxists.org/archive/hardcastle/1947/02/railways.htm" id="mwDY8">"The Nationalisation of the Railways"</a>. <i id="mwDZA"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Socialist_Standard" title="Socialist Standard" id="mwDZE">Socialist Standard</a></i>. <b id="mwDZI">43</b> (1)<span class="reference-accessdate" id="mwDZM">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap" id="mwDZQ">28 April</span> 2007</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Socialist+Standard&amp;rft.atitle=The+Nationalisation+of+the+Railways&amp;rft.volume=43&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.date=1947&amp;rft.aulast=Hardcastle&amp;rft.aufirst=Edgar&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.marxists.org%2Farchive%2Fhardcastle%2F1947%2F02%2Frailways.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt1733" id="mwDZU"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt1733" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwDZY"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-349" id="cite_note-349"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-349" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-349" class="mw-reference-text"><i id="mwDZc">Comparing Economic Systems in the Twenty-First Century</i>, 2003, by Gregory and Stuart. <link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt1739" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"ISBN","href":"./Template:ISBN"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"0-618-26181-8"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwDZg"/><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" about="#mwt1739" id="mwDZk">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt1739" id="mwDZo"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/0-618-26181-8" title="Special:BookSources/0-618-26181-8" about="#mwt1739" id="mwDZs">0-618-26181-8</a>. p. 142: "It is an economic system that combines social ownership of capital with market allocation of capital...The state owns the means of production, and returns accrue to society at large."</span></li><li about="#cite_note-350" id="cite_note-350"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-350" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-350" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation book" about="#mwt1740" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite book ","href":"./Template:Cite_book"},"params":{"last":{"wt":"Bockman"},"first":{"wt":"Johanna"},"title":{"wt":"Markets in the name of Socialism: The Left-Wing origins of Neoliberalism"},"publisher":{"wt":"Stanford University Press"},"year":{"wt":"2011"},"isbn":{"wt":"978-0-8047-7566-3"},"page":{"wt":"21"},"quote":{"wt":"For Walras, socialism would provide the necessary institutions for free competition and social justice. Socialism, in Walras&apos;s view, entailed state ownership of land and natural resources and the abolition of income taxes. As owner of land and natural resources, the state could then lease these resources to many individuals and groups, which would eliminate monopolies and thus enable free competition. The leasing of land and natural resources would also provide enough state revenue to make income taxes unnecessary, allowing a worker to invest his savings and become &apos;an owner or capitalist at the same time that he remains a worker."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwDZw">Bockman, Johanna (2011). <i id="mwDZ0">Markets in the name of Socialism: The Left-Wing origins of Neoliberalism</i>. Stanford University Press. p.<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwDZ4"> </span>21. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number" id="mwDZ8">ISBN</a><span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwDaA"> </span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Special:BookSources/978-0-8047-7566-3" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-8047-7566-3" id="mwDaE">978-0-8047-7566-3</a>. <q id="mwDaI">For Walras, socialism would provide the necessary institutions for free competition and social justice. Socialism, in Walras's view, entailed state ownership of land and natural resources and the abolition of income taxes. As owner of land and natural resources, the state could then lease these resources to many individuals and groups, which would eliminate monopolies and thus enable free competition. The leasing of land and natural resources would also provide enough state revenue to make income taxes unnecessary, allowing a worker to invest his savings and become 'an owner or capitalist at the same time that he remains a worker.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Markets+in+the+name+of+Socialism%3A+The+Left-Wing+origins+of+Neoliberalism&amp;rft.pages=21&amp;rft.pub=Stanford+University+Press&amp;rft.date