p. 14 "Anarchism is the view that a society without the state, or government, is both possible and desirable."</span></li><li about="#cite_note-369" id="cite_note-369"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-369" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-369" class="mw-reference-text">Sheehan, Sean. Anarchism, London: Reaktion Books Ltd., 2004. p. 85</span></li><li about="#cite_note-iaf-ifa.org-370" id="cite_note-iaf-ifa.org-370"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-iaf-ifa.org_370-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-iaf-ifa.org_370-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-iaf-ifa.org_370-2"><span class="mw-linkback-text">3 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-iaf-ifa.org-370" class="mw-reference-text"><cite class="citation web" about="#mwt1998" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"cite web ","href":"./Template:Cite_web"},"params":{"url":{"wt":"http://www.iaf-ifa.org/principles/english.html"},"title":{"wt":"IAF principles"},"publisher":{"wt":"[[International of Anarchist Federations]]"},"archiveurl":{"wt":"https://web.archive.org/web/20120105095946/http://www.iaf-ifa.org/principles/english.html"},"archivedate":{"wt":"5 January 2012"},"deadurl":{"wt":"yes"},"quote":{"wt":"The IAF – IFA fights for : the abolition of all forms of authority whether economical, political, social, religious, cultural or sexual."}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwDgM"><a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20120105095946/http://www.iaf-ifa.org/principles/english.html" id="mwDgQ">"IAF principles"</a>. <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_of_Anarchist_Federations" title="International of Anarchist Federations" id="mwDgU">International of Anarchist Federations</a>. Archived from <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.iaf-ifa.org/principles/english.html" id="mwDgY">the original</a> on 5 January 2012. <q id="mwDgc">The IAF – IFA fights for<span typeof="mw:DisplaySpace mw:Placeholder" id="mwDgg"> </span>: the abolition of all forms of authority whether economical, political, social, religious, cultural or sexual.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=IAF+principles&amp;rft.pub=International+of+Anarchist+Federations&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.iaf-ifa.org%2Fprinciples%2Fenglish.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASocialism" class="Z3988" about="#mwt1998" id="mwDgk"></span><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r879151008" about="#mwt1998" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Module:Citation/CS1/styles.css"},"body":{"extsrc":""}}' id="mwDgo"/></span></li><li about="#cite_note-371" id="cite_note-371"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-371" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-371" class="mw-reference-text">"as many anarchists have stressed, it is not government as such that they find objectionable, but the hierarchical forms of government associated with the nation state." Judith Suissa. <i id="mwDgs">Anarchism and Education: a Philosophical Perspective</i>. Routledge. New York. 2006. p. 7</span></li><li about="#cite_note-372" id="cite_note-372"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-372" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-372" class="mw-reference-text">"That is why Anarchy, when it works to destroy authority in all its aspects, when it demands the abrogation of laws and the abolition of the mechanism that serves to impose them, when it refuses all hierarchical organisation and preaches free agreement—at the same time strives to maintain and enlarge the precious kernel of social customs without which no human or animal society can exist." <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Peter_Kropotkin" title="Peter Kropotkin" id="mwDgw">Peter Kropotkin</a>. <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.theanarchistlibrary.org/HTML/Petr_Kropotkin__Anarchism__its_philosophy_and_ideal.html" id="mwDg0">Anarchism: its philosophy and ideal</a></span></li><li about="#cite_note-373" id="cite_note-373"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-373" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-373" class="mw-reference-text">"anarchists are opposed to irrational (e.g., illegitimate) authority, in other words, hierarchy—hierarchy being the institutionalisation of authority within a society." <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="http://www.theanarchistlibrary.org/HTML/The_Anarchist_FAQ_Editorial_Collective__An_Anarchist_FAQ__03_17_.html#toc2" id="mwDg4">"B.1 Why are anarchists against authority and hierarchy?"</a> in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./An_Anarchist_FAQ" title="An Anarchist FAQ" id="mwDg8">An Anarchist FAQ</a></span></li><li about="#cite_note-definition-374" id="cite_note-definition-374"><a href="./Socialism#cite_ref-definition_374-0" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-definition-374" class="mw-reference-text">
